 <p>Aldrin of the Nexus<BR>
<a href="http://www.xtimports.com/index.html"><img src="http://www.xtimports.com/data/Everquest/pics/Aldrinsig2.jpg" alt="Extra Terrestrial Imports " align="left" border="0" hspace="0" width="240" height="263"></a></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f7f7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub95.ezboard.com/uugle.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Ugle</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Warmly Poster</span><br> <font color=#778899>(2/4/02 4:51:47 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub95.ezboard.com/finnoruukserverfrm11.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=207.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://ugleduklin.tripod.com/sitebuildercontent/sitebuilderpictures/dscn0011s.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Hardware geeks wanted... advice needed.</span><hr size=1> You could also go with 180GB drives for SCSI, though the biggest IDE I've seen advertised is 120GB which isn't too bad.  Also, you can get SCSI CD-ROM's, SCSI CD-RW's, SCSI ZIP drives, and SCSI hard drives.  One SCSI chain and you could support all of this, with the added advantage of being able to transfer data between devices without having to go over the system bus like you would with your multiple IDE controllers.  And it's far less taxing on your CPU.  But it is pricier.  I'm thinking looking at your other components like the Geforce2 that price is an issue, and I think rather then worry about three IDE channels you'd be better off just getting one 100GB+ Hard drive rather then trying to piece together the three that you have.  That would then leave you two channels for the CD/DVD drives and one for the Zip drive. <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <br><font color=#778899>- </font><a href=http://pub95.ezboard.com/binnoruukserver>Innoruuk Server</a><font color=#778899> - </font><a href=http://pub95.ezboard.com/finnoruukserverfrm11>Innoruuk - OOC</a> <font color=#778899> - </fon